Compute $\arcsin(\sin 66^\circ-\sin 54^\circ)$ in degrees.
inference:
Using the trigonometric identity $\sin(A-B)=\sin A \cos B - \cos A \sin B$, we have:

$$\arcsin(\sin 66^\circ-\sin 54^\circ) = \arcsin(2\sin 12^\circ \cos 54^\circ)$$

Using the trigonometric identity $\cos A = \sqrt{1-\sin^2 A}$, we have:

$$\arcsin(2\sin 12^\circ \cos 54^\circ) = \arcsin(2\sin 12^\circ \sqrt{1-\sin^2 54^\circ})$$

Now, we can use a calculator to evaluate $\arcsin(2\sin 12^\circ \sqrt{1-\sin^2 54^\circ})$:

$$\arcsin(2\sin 12^\circ \sqrt{1-\sin^2 54^\circ}) \approx 10.99^\circ$$

Final Answer: $\boxed{10.99^\circ}.$ I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
From the sum-to-product formula,
\[ \sin x- \sin z = 2\sin \frac{x-z}{2}\cos\frac{x+z}{2}.\]Applying this with $x = 66^{\circ}$ and $z = 54^{\circ}$, we have
\begin{align*}
\arcsin(\sin 66^\circ-\sin54^\circ)&=\arcsin \Big(2\sin\frac{66^\circ -54^\circ }{2}\cos\frac{66^\circ +54^\circ }{2} \Big)\\
&=\arcsin(2\sin6^\circ\cos 60^\circ)\\
&=\arcsin(\sin 6^\circ) \\
&= \boxed{6^{\circ}}.
\end{align*}
